Subject: [PATCH 3/3] x86_64: relocate the GOT in static links

The relocation walk explicitly skips s1->got -- correct for dynamic output,
where the loader fills the GOT at load time, and fatal for -static, where
nobody ever will: every slot stays zero. tcc itself emits R_X86_64_GOTPCREL
data accesses (newlib's `stderr`/`errno` are _impure_ptr dereferences; even
some file-static accesses go through the GOT), so any nontrivial static
binary dereferences NULL on its first stdio or errno touch.

Found by EmbLinkOS target #3 -- EmbBuild rebuilding EmbBuild: the TCC-built
build tool crashed at CR2=0 in parse_manifest, writing its own stanza
counter through an unfilled GOT slot. Smaller programs (tally, sysinfo)
survived by luck: their only GOT slots sat in unvisited error paths.

Sibling of patch 0001 (static PLT32->PC32): same disease, one table over.
The fix is one condition -- the GOT's relocations (GLOB_DAT against symtab,
already emitted by put_got_entry, already handled by the relocator) simply
get applied when static_link is set.
---
--- a/tccelf.c
+++ b/tccelf.c
@@ -1850,8 +1850,16 @@
         /* On X86 gdb 7.3 works in any case but gdb 6.6 will crash if SHF_ALLOC
         checking is removed */
 #else
-        if (s->reloc && s != s1->got)
-        /* On X86_64 gdb 7.3 will crash if SHF_ALLOC checking is present */
+        if (s->reloc && (s != s1->got || s1->static_link))
+        /* On X86_64 gdb 7.3 will crash if SHF_ALLOC checking is present.
+           EmbLink patch 0003 (sibling of 0001's PLT fix): in a STATIC link
+           there is no dynamic loader to fill the GOT, yet tcc emits
+           R_X86_64_GOTPCREL data accesses (e.g. every newlib `stderr` =
+           _impure_ptr deref) whose slots would stay ZERO -- a guaranteed
+           NULL dereference at the first errno/stdio touch. The GOT's own
+           relocs (GLOB_DAT against symtab) are already emitted by
+           put_got_entry and the relocator already handles them; the walk
+           just skipped the section. Relocate it when static. */
 #endif
             relocate_section(s1, s);
     }
